Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis

Marks: 60

Context

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Food Preparation Time by Cuisine Type

In[33]:
# display boxplot to visualize the distribution of 'food_preparation_time' for different 'cuisine_type'
plt.figure(figsize=(15,6)) #reconfigure size
plt.title('boxplot: Food Preparation Time by Cuisine Type') #title
plt.xlabel('Cuisine Type') #x-axis label

sns.boxplot(data=df, x='cuisine_type', y='food_preparation_time', hue='cuisine_type', palette='pastel');

  • The above boxplot shows the median food preparation time being fairly consistent across cuisine types. This suggests that restaurants maintain a predictable cooking time regardless of cuisine type.

  • Among the four most popular cuisines, Japanese and Italian have slightly higher prep time compared to American and Chinese. This difference could be due to the complexity in food preparing techniques.

  • The IQR varies across cuisines, suggesting certain dishes might require more preparation which increases the preparation time.

  • Consumers might lean towards faster prepared cuisines, but it can be dependant on others factors such as cost and quality of the food.

Rating vs. Food Preparation Time

In[34]:
# Display catplot in pointplot form to visualize overall relation between rating and food preparation time
sns.catplot(data=df, x='rating', y='food_preparation_time', kind='point'); #pointplot
plt.xlabel('Rating') #x-axis label
plt.ylabel('Food Preparation Time') #y-axis label
plt.title('Rating vs. Food Preparation Time') #title
plt.show()
  • The above plot shows that higher ratings tend to align with moderate food preparation times, suggesting that customers appreciate a balance between speed and quality.
  • Lower ratings are not necessarily due to longer preparation times, suggesting that customers may be fine with longer waits if the food quality meets their expectations.
  • Lower ratings show a wider spread in food preparation time. This can indicate there is a inconsistency in service which could be a problem. If food preparation time is taking longer than expected by the customers, could lead to a downgrade in rating satisfaction.
  • An audit system of restaurants should be put in place. This implemented in conjunction with customer feedback reviews can help to resolve inconsistencies that customers may find unsatisfactory.

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]

In[46]:
# Calculate profit margin per order using a lambda to apply if-else conditional statement to each order
df['fixed_margin'] = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(lambda x: x * 0.25 if x > 20 else (x * 0.15 if x > 5 else 0))

# Compute total net revenue by taking sum of df['fixed_margin']
net_revenue = df['fixed_margin'].sum()

#display net revenue total
print(f"Company net revenue: ${net_revenue:.2f}")

Company net revenue: $6166.30

Observations:

  • The net revenue of Foodhub was $6166.30.
  • There is room to improve the total net revenue by increasing customer order volume and having more higher priced orders. This can involve targeted promotionals to get customers interested and exclusive deals on certain items such as on larger ticket items or add-ons items when buying large combo orders.There should be a primary focus on improving ratings by carefully reviewing customer feedback and acting on areas of concern.

Conclusion and Recommendations

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]

Conclusions:

The analysis has found several trends in customer behavior, order characteristics and operational efficiency:

  • American cuisine is the most popular cuisine type to order among the customers. It has the most popular restaurant. Along with Japanese, Italian and Chinese, these form the major popular choices. The top five choices all fall within these categories. The high order volume shows strong customer preference. Restaurant popularity drives order volume, so Foodhub should leverage these popular cuisines by strengthening partnerships with these particular restaurants.
  • The weekend dominates order volume with over 70% of orders made on weekends, particularly for American cuisine. Strategic promotions could capitalize on this trend.
  • Customer ratings need improvement, with 39% having no rating. This indicates low customer engagement with feedback. Most given ratings are 5 stars, but lower ratings correlate with inconsistencies in prep or delivery times.
  • High-Cost Orders comprise 29%. with Nearly 30% of orders cost more than $20, showing opportunities for premium purchases.
  • Delivery efficiency varies with delivery times generally quicker on weekends, with weekdays slowed down by traffic congestion.
  • Ratings correlate with moderate prep and faster delivery, with customers prefering a balance of food quality and speed. Inconsistencies lead to lower ratings.

Recommendations:

  • Via collaborative partnerships with the most popular restaurants in the most popular cuisine types, a promotional strategy can be devised to offer appealing exclusive deals that will drive customer engagement. The restaurants can be offered premium visibility on the app or negotiated commision rates to drive sales.

  • Foodgrub should offer weekend promotions to capitalize on peak ordering periods. Special weekend exclusive promotions can drive engagement. Alternatively, surge pricing can boost Foodgrubs revenue. Strategic weekday discounts can be offered to boost engagement during slower periods.

  • A new robust rating review system needs to be implemented to increase customer engagement. The users should be incentivized in leaving ratings by offering rewards such as exclusive discounts or loyalty points that can be accumulated and used for purchases. This feedback can be used to refine service by addressing inconsistencies in food preparation and delivery time.

  • A possible option to increase net revenue, is a strategy to try and work around most customers overall preference for an affordable cost order, is to offer promotional deals for higher priced orders. Promote high cost orders with bundle deals or waive delivery fees to encourage premium purchases.

  • An audit system of restaurants should be put in place. This implemented in conjunction with customer feedback reviews can help to resolve inconsistencies that customers may find unsatisfactory.

  • To address longer weekday delivery times on weekdays and in general, routing strategies need to be looked at and improved upon when needed. Implementing an advanced route optimization software program to find quickest routes could minimize delivery times. It would be important to compile data and create a heatmap tracking when and where deliveries typically take place and apportion the appropriate amount of delivery drivers to meet requirements to keep delivery times down. Having a versatile fleet of vehicles, such as the inclusion of scooters and delivery bikes could help improve delivery times. If not already utilized, a real-time visibility tool should be employed to keep customers informed about their order status, which can boost transparency and trust.

  • It is a astute idea to offer promotional advertisement to restaurants which meet high standard rating criteria. Greater visibility could provide an increase in order volume for the restaurant, which would incentivize restaurants to try to improve their ratings.
